<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-07-23T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-07-23T16:00:00-05:00" n="407" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d407">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. No. 814.01B/2</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Minister in Guatemala</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_LWH1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Leavell</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-07-23T17:00:00-04:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">July 23, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Your July 15, 12 noon. The Government of the United States, in
                                considering the question of enemy properties, has taken the attitude
                                that (1) the transfer of the physical assets of German properties to
                                    <pb facs="0451" n="367" xml:id="pg_367"/> non-enemies be free
                                from all enemy of any character and from all obligations or
                                contracts to enemies, and (2) the proceeds of the sale of these
                                physical assets should be held, the ultimate disposition to be
                                determined at the termination of the war. This is also believed to
                                be the attitude of Great Britain and France.</p>
                            <p>Communicate this to the Government of Guatemala and also to
                                    <persName>Hodgsdon</persName>, expressing the hope that the
                                Government of Guatemala will take a similar attitude with respect to
                                enemy properties.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_PFL1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>